content: Dear renju fans, I am glad to announce to opening of new series of lessons.
In the following weeks or months, we will learn different aspects of renju tactics.
we have been waiting it for a long time :-)
All of these small aspects combined together makes you a strongest player.
tieuphilac, aivo, shuwang, nick_hopper, span, Intotherenju, Renjufans, moocheng, luwenzhe, killer21st, Ikon, namic_99, Jasny_sokol, bomb, Chancewu, Sakuma, Alan, jahre, L8RG8R, NZ21568377, wetcat.
One of the key terms of renju tactics is 'tempo'.
Do you know what it means?
The word tempo is widely used in different fields, including sports ad music, etc.
In general, it is related to speed.
Chinese shall call 节奏 I believe
In renju, we dont have 'speed', so you may wonder, what is the use of that term named 'tempo'.
We often use the phrases 'get tempo', 'keep tempo', 'lose tempo'...
guess : do right thing at right time.
no, its nothing about right or wrong,
if we imagine renju game as run race between two payers,
then the one who is leading, has a tempo.
and another one has no choice but follow the leader.
Do you know bicycle races... the one who rides in first position doesnt always win.. sometimes to be behind is better
same in renju... to have tempo is not always good
sometimes is better to let opponent take the lead and let him attack
It is all clear so far.
how to know, when it is good to have tempo and when it is better let opponent be active.
I am sorry. I will behave.
To know this well, it takes long time..
Very often, even 9 dan players will make a mistake in judgement of tempo.
when u knew this, u got first WC?
The best way to learn it is through examples.
I will start with the position from my game with Hayakawa in WC.
ando RT is black in that game?
I was black and I lost,
the loss made me analyse the variant more
and notice the issues of tempo there.
DO NOT ATTEMPT TO GET THE TEMPO IF YOU HAVE NOTHING USEFUL TO DO WITH IT.
Many players fight severely over a tempo,
but winner is the one who saw the outcome of the exchanges of tempo.
For example, at this moment, black is active..
but white has two choices here:
1. to defend passively and let black continue attacking.
2. to play actively and gain tempo.
Since black cannot do his own stuff anymore, and has to follow whites,
so we say "white got the tempo".
Was it good to get this tempo?
And it may take long time even for top players to decide.
Even I lost the game, it took me 3 hours of analyses to decide if tempo was good for white.
For example, in case of passive style,
but at the same time, if white survives this,
then upper side will be very promising for white,
because, there will be even more white stones than now.
For example the stone 16 will make upper side even stronger
So, all that white needs is to stay cool and defend.
But there is always a risk of defense failure or mistake.
White will be active now, forcing black to defend.
The good side of this is.. maybe white can keep up the tempo and develop until it has winning power.
But for example, if white is unable to keep up the 'steam',
then sooner or later white attack fails,
and then black is powerful on both left and right sides.
Which one is good, hard to say.
So, we can say tempo is a method, not a goal.
So you wait until you know you can sustain the attack?
In general, there may be many kinds of needs for tempo.
One simple usage is to get tempo to win right away by VCT.
Second usage is to use tempo for defense purposes,
for example, having tempo, you can use you 'useless' attack power just to fill up the part of the board,
so that opponent has no good attack area left after you lose tempo.
The second way is widely used.
It was my game with Nakamura.
i still had the tempo as you see,
white was forced to follow blacks
So, I used the tempo to make several moves which have important value in the aspect of defense.
Here, a good defense, while still keeping tempo.
Had I given up tempo too soon, I would lose the game because the space for white future attacks was still too big.
So, I kept up the tempo.
the reason was - black needs tempo so badly,
so it cannot afford blocking everything at this point
As you see, ever since the move 13, black did not lose tempo at all,
And now, white realizing that such continuous black tempo will 'eat up' all the potential white space,
so Nakamura made a brave attempt,
using this 26th move, that says clearly:
"you won't get the left lower corner with your tempo"
so, white realized that tempo was used to fill up the board,
and thats why the active 26th was made
else, black will fill all 4 corners
and even if black doesnt win after that, the draw is ensured.
That explains why he used such 26.
It was his weapon against tempo that was eating his space.
to take another good white spot
notice if white takes it instead
and after 27, black STILL has the tempo
White has lost all good potential attack points, while still under the pressure of opponents
And further moves are not so important..
by connecting lower side over the left wing
to make passive 26 will give white  0% chance to win this game
so he made active 26, risky, but if stands, then white has some chances to win later
When I made moves 13, 15, 17.. I had no hope of win...
I knew he could always choose draw by being passive
And to avoid loss, all the moves that you saw were necessary
almost any other way would let black run out of power,
and then white could take over tempo while free space is still big enough.
some of you may not recognize mirror
the one you just saw before was the 3rd
Here, although black has 3 offence lines
black chose to give up tempo
Ando was black in all 6 games
This is a very important moment
Should black keep tempo or not.
but then you will think of the result,
what if you will fail the e11 attack,
then it will be too late to defend both left and right side,
white will be strong at left
so, before going to e11, you have to secure at least one side
and black must secure the side by using tempo,
and it has to be done so that black will keep the tempo.
Now, the right side is safe.
White will not have enough power to attack there,
Move 30 speaks same words as the move 26 in previous game -
I had thought you were planning for future connection to left. But it was defense!
"I wont let you use your tempo to crawl to upper area and fill it"
in another lesson, we learn attack techniques,
and someday in future, we learn, the great player can combine many tehniques into one stone
So, speaking of the aspect of tempo,
understand. But don't know how to do it :)
the move 30 tries to cut off blacks from coming to upper side.
hard to me to do it.
yes, 30 is like 26 in the other game
Now, the right wing is pretty safe,
but the super-good 30 and 32 ruined black plans a bit:
black had counted that the tempo will do all the good job by securing on of two dangerous sides,
but good stones 30 and 32 created a new potential are for white while black was filling up right wing.
Now, white had strong upper space and left space.
So, black was still facing two potential white areas,
so, it was still early to go to e11.
So, black used the lower side source, to neutralize left side.
Move 33 creates a VCT in the botton
Can't feel white's strength on top
But move 34 was kind of unexpected
It was not as though as 30 and 32
So, this relatively poor 34 allowed black to secure left side without further problems
So, now it was safe to go to e11... finally..
As you see, it was an obvious point long time ago..
but before black took that point,
So many thoughts under each move!
one had to think if the tempo could serve some other purposes first
and in this case, tempo did good fill-up job
i dont know why i said e11 ;) pardon me
of course, in the lesson of attacks in the future,
and see how the stone 33... point j9 etc, helped the attack of e10
but it is not important in today's lesson about Tempo
the game ended few moves after
so, actually, while black was systematically manipulating with tempo,
the chance of win came by itself
as opponent was doing wild attempts to break the use of tempo.
the defense is not todays topic, so i skip further analysis today
we will review same game many times in future
Now, going back to the main diagram of today's lesson,

tieuphilac, span, moocheng, luwenzhe, Renjufans, Sakuma, shuwang, Ikon, wetcat, nick_hopper, tunnet99, L8RG8R, namic_99, Chancewu, Jasny_sokol, killer21st, bomb, yyfcsd, NZ21568377, aivo, Intotherenju, Alan.
We were standing on crossroads.. and trying to decide the best path...
I tell you, although tempo should be a tactical tool, and only be used when needed,
most players in the world are too emotional,
and their passion of game decides their use of tempo.
So players always hunt the tempo while others will stay behind,
even when there is a chance to go.
A great player is also a great bluffer sometimes.
To offer the opponent to go to attack is a brave move..
Nakamura is the biggest gambler in the world when it comes to offering dangerous tempos to opponents
There were tens of games where Nakamura gives win chances to opponent.
if you sit against Nakamura, and he gives you tempo,
you dont want to belive this tempo is relaly useful
so you will give it back to him
he did it oh so many times..
if we ever had a chance to sit against him?
you can sometimes do it when you are so strong
like your first game with him?
and others fear you so much
my first game was exception, there he had home analysis
but some of his games he plays wildly by feeling.
a great and brave man indeed.
This is what I admire about him,
the courage to give out crazy tempos.
you get tempo with good win potential, you go for it,
So most Japanese, whenever get tempo from nakamura,
they launch a big attack, directly, strongly...
um,so strange man ..now i wanna know which 16 did he choose next.
My style was unexpected for him,
he gave me same wild tempo as he gave to many others before
but he did not expect that i will manipulate with this tempo
and use it for many tactical purposes
that is the main reason of the match result
as we saw two previous examples,
He would have regret for giving you the tempo :)
tempo was used as main tactical tool.
did you know that he gave you the tempp in purpose?
Now, the game you see on screen is my game from 1999,
(I knew he was going to give me tempo, as I analysed his previous games)
and my next foolish move ended the game
I was too greedy at the bottom
But if 19 here, all game would be different.
White is still active, but not so sure to win anymore...
and here is the puzzling moments
of who really has the tempo
so white does not need it
for example, black will try some wild move
it takes lots of analyses, whether there is vct or not..
I began to analyse this 18th move
since white's main idea was to add black stone to h7,
so, how about this 18 immediately here
there was also an interesting response,
which really makes the whole variant chaotic
So, when I studied this 18th move here, I had to check same 19th move
Black tries to take away the tempo
firstly, tempo would help to block some of white stuff,
and secondly, in case of passive style we saw that white would practically wi
so, the active 19 as an attempt to gain tempo was necessary.
GM yyfcsd wil show right moves
Can you explain this move, yy?
This 20th move is the only way for white - it creates a 4x3 threat, after which  white has no blocks.
white has a tempo now.and well-commect with 12.
As you see, this beautiful 20th move led white to win
so the attempt to gain tempo with move 19 failed
But passive style is so poor here.
white can now build the attack freely
If white did not have such beautiful win
but still... black had strong right side before playing 19
black used the tempo to fill up upper side
Isn't it the tactic we learned?
interesting idea of defense... but as I said.. it always has two sides..
now black has lost power on right
with the price of surviving longer
but shaoping's example was still useful for us..
because it just showed one possible usage of tempo again
So, what is the conclusion here?
is tempo good for white or not?
indeed, we did not look carefully the second way that is passive style
we should analyse both ways as far as possible
from what we saw today here,
we can say the active style looks fine at least.
We did not find any moment of danger where white could lose
So, great Haywakawa chose this 14 without doubt.
But knowing him, I must say he played it by feeling
not by analysing the final outcome of tempo
So, his feeling was right this time.
g11 is the most played move here
The problem of black here is:
Black has only one strong side, that is right side, and no tempo
which means, white can forever attack on left.
And it is so unlikely black can survive it
anyway, I believe you all got the idea of todays lesson.. how to evaluate the use of tempo
and how to manipulate with tempo.
got the idea, but hard to use it
The exact analysis of this variant is not that important.
Because this is not analysis lesson.
